{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637889"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:46:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:46:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17676"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.05,0.05,0.2,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10507"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe kidneys maintain homeostasis through filtration, reabsorption and secretion. Tubular secretion is an essential process that moves substances from blood into the tubular lumen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the process of tubular secretion in the kidneys?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active transport from peritubular capillaries to tubule lumen","Movement of substances from tubule to blood","Filtration through glomerular membrane","Passive diffusion across tubular cells","Ion exchange in the loop of Henle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETubular secretion involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive transport from peritubular capillaries to tubule lumen\u003C/strong\u003E. This process requires energy in the form of ATP and specific transport proteins to move substances against their concentration gradients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of substances from tubule to blood\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes reabsorption, which occurs in the opposite direction to secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFiltration through glomerular membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes glomerular filtration, the initial step of urine formation, not tubular secretion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion across tubular cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretion is an active process requiring energy, not passive diffusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIon exchange in the loop of Henle\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the countercurrent multiplication system for concentrating urine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportant substances secreted include potassium ions (primarily in the collecting duct), hydrogen ions (for pH regulation), and various organic anions like penicillin. This process helps eliminate waste products and maintain electrolyte balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tubular secretion actively transports substances from peritubular capillaries into the renal tubule lumen against concentration gradients.","Common substances secreted by renal tubules include potassium, hydrogen ions, and organic anions like penicillin.","Tubular secretion occurs primarily in the proximal tubule and collecting duct through specific transport proteins that require ATP."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17676"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T22:42:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T22:43:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78237"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup